# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cloudflare-d1
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare was founded in 2009 by Matthew Prince, Lee Holloway, and Michelle Zatlyn.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The company went public on the New York Stock Exchange in 2019 under the ticker symbol NET.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare has since expanded its offerings to include edge computing through its Workers platform, a public DNS resolver (1.1.1.1), and a VPN-like service known as WARP.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In recent years, the company has integrated artificial intelligence into its infrastructure, acquiring companies such as Replicate and launching tools to manage AI bots and scrapers.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] According to W3Techs, Cloudflare is used by approximately 21.3% of all websites on the Internet as of January 2026.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The company has been the subject of controversy regarding its policy of content neutrality.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare has also faced criticism and litigation regarding copyright infringement by websites using its services, notably losing a lawsuit against Japanese publishers in 2025.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The company experienced significant global outages in late 2025 which disrupted services for major platforms internationally.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare was founded on July 26, 2009, by Matthew Prince, Lee Holloway, and Michelle Zatlyn.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Prince and Holloway had previously collaborated on Project Honey Pot, a product of Unspam Technologies that partly inspired the basis of Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2009, the company was venture-capital funded.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] On August 15, 2019, Cloudflare submitted its S-1 filing for an initial public offering on the New York Stock Exchange under the stock ticker NET.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] It opened for public trading on September 13, 2019, at $15 per share.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2020, Cloudflare co-founder and COO Michelle Zatlyn was named president.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare has acquired web-services and security companies, including StopTheHacker (February 2014), CryptoSeal (June 2014), Eager Platform Co.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Replicate (November 2025), and Human Native (January 2026).
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Since at least 2017, Cloudflare has used a wall of lava lamps at its San Francisco headquarters as a source of randomness for encryption keys, alongside double pendulums at its London offices and a Geiger counter at its Singapore offices.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The lava lamp installation implements the Lavarand method, where a camera transforms the unpredictable shapes of the "lava" blobs into a digital image.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In Q4 2022, Cloudflare provided paid services to 162,086 customers.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In October 2024, Cloudflare won a lawsuit against patent troll Sable Networks.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Sable paid Cloudflare $225,000, granted it a royalty-free license to its patent portfolio, and dedicated its patents to the public by abandoning its patent rights.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In November 2025, it was announced Cloudflare had agreed to acquire Replicate, a San Francisco–based platform that enables software developers to run, fine-tune, and deploy open-source machine-learning models via an API without managing infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In January 2026, Cloudflare released an analysis regarding BGP routing leaks observed from the Venezuelan state-owned ISP CANTV (AS8048), which occurred on January 2 coincides with the arrest of Nicolás Maduro.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] While some security researchers had speculated that the outages were linked to U.S. cyber operations, Cloudflare's data indicated that the anomalies were consistent with a pattern of "insufficient routing export and import policies" by the ISP rather than malicious external interference.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In January 2026, Cloudflare acquired Human Native, an AI data marketplace that brokers transactions between developers and content creators, for an undisclosed amount.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] On January 16, 2026, Cloudflare acquired The Astro Technology Company, the developers behind the open-source web framework Astro.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In May 2026, Cloudflare announced the elimination of approximately 1,100 positions, around 20 percent of its workforce, in a restructuring the company attributed to the rapid adoption of artificial intelligence tools.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The announcement coincided with the company's first-quarter 2026 earnings, which reported a record $639.8 million in quarterly revenue, a 34 percent year-over-year increase.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] CEO Matthew Prince stated the cuts were not driven by performance concerns but reflected roles made obsolete by AI, and that Cloudflare expected to employ more people by the end of 2027 than at any point during 2026.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare provides network and security products for consumers and businesses, utilizing edge computing, reverse proxies for web traffic, data center interconnects, and a content distribution network to serve content across its network of servers.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] It supports transport layer protocols TCP, UDP, QUIC, and many application layer protocols such as DNS over HTTPS, SMTP, and HTTP/2 with support for HTTP/2 Server Push.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] As of 2023, Cloudflare handles an average of 45 million HTTP requests per second.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] As of 2024, Cloudflare servers are powered by AMD EPYC 9684X processors.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare also provides analysis and reports on large-scale outages, including Verizon's October 2024 outage.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In April 2026, Cloudflare released an open-source CMS called EmDash, intended to align with serverless and edge-based architecture.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2023, Cloudflare launched "Workers AI", a framework allowing for use of Nvidia GPU's within Cloudflare's network.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2024, Cloudflare launched a tool that prevents bots from scraping websites.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] To build automatic bot detector models, the company analyzed "AI" bots and crawler traffic.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The company also launched an "AI" assistant to generate charts based on queries by leveraging "Workers AI".
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare announced plans in September 2024 to launch a marketplace where website owners can sell "AI" model providers access to scrape their site's content.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In March 2025, Cloudflare announced a new feature called "AI Labyrinth", which combats unauthorized "AI" data scraping by serving fake "AI"-generated content to LLM bots.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In July, the company rolled out a permission-based setting to allow websites to automatically block online bots from scraping data and content.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare released AutoRAG into beta in 2025.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] AutoRAG (retrieval augmented generation) creates a vector database of a website's unstructured content to identify relationships between concepts.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] It is part of an initiative with Microsoft, alongside their NLWeb standard, to make websites easier for people and automated systems to query.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare and GoDaddy partnered in April 2026 to enable AI Crawl Control features on GoDaddy hosted websites.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] This would allow site owners to decide how AI bot crawlers interact with their content.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare provides free and paid DDoS mitigation services that protect customers from distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare received media attention in June 2011 for providing DDoS mitigation for the website of LulzSec, a black hat hacking group.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In March 2013, The Spamhaus Project was targeted by a DDoS attack that Cloudflare reported exceeded 300 gigabits per second (Gbit/s).
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Patrick Gilmore, of Akamai, stated that at the time it was "the largest publicly announced DDoS attack in the history of the Internet".
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] While trying to defend Spamhaus against the DDoS attacks, Cloudflare ended up being attacked as well; Google and other companies eventually came to Spamhaus' defense and helped it to absorb the unprecedented amount of attack traffic.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2014, Cloudflare began providing free DDoS mitigation for artists, activists, journalists, and human rights groups under the name "Project Galileo".
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2017, it extended the service to electoral infrastructure and political campaigns under the name "Athenian Project".
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] By 2025, more than 2,900 users and organizations were participating in Project Galileo, including 31 US states.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In February 2014, Cloudflare claimed to have mitigated an NTP reflection attack against an unnamed European customer, which it stated peaked at 400 Gbit/s.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In November 2014, it reported a 500 Gbit/s DDoS attack in Hong Kong.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In July 2021, the company claimed to have absorbed a DDoS attack three times larger than any it had previously recorded, which its corporate blog implied was over 1.2 Tbit/s in total.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In February 2023, Cloudflare reported blocking a 71 million request-per-second DDoS attack which "the company says was the largest HTTP DDoS attack on record".
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare blocked the then largest publicly recorded DDoS attack in August 2025, with volumetric attacks peaking at 11.5 terabits per second (tbps).
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] This was surpassed in December 2025 when an Aisuru botnet launched a 31.4 tbps attack, with a requests-per-second rate exceeding 200 million, against multiple companies in the telecommunications sector, a campaign Cloudflare dubbed "The Night Before Christmas".
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In April 2026, Cloudflare released a system designed to let users implement their own custom DDoS mitigation logic, using protocols built on User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2017, Cloudflare launched Cloudflare Workers, a serverless computing platform for creating new applications, augmenting existing ones, without configuring or maintaining infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] It has expanded to include Workers KV, a low-latency key-value data store; Cron Triggers, for scheduling Cron jobs; and additional tooling for developers to deploy and scale their code across the globe.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2020, Cloudflare released a JAMstack platform for developers to deploy websites on Cloudflare's Edge infrastructure, under the name "Pages".
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2022, Cloudflare announced an Edge SQL database, D1, which is built on SQLite.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In August 2023, Cloudflare and IBM announced a partnership providing bot management capabilities to protect IBM Cloud customers from malicious bots and automated threats.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The same month, Cloudflare was hired by SpaceX to boost the performance of Starlink.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In September, the company launched Cloudflare Fonts as a competitor to Google Fonts.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In April 2020, Cloudflare announced it was moving away from using reCAPTCHA in favor of hCaptcha.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In September 2022, Cloudflare began to test Turnstile – an alternative to CAPTCHA.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The product, instead of presenting a visual CAPTCHA for the user to solve, automatizes the verification process by conducting JavaScript-based checks inside the browser to determine whether the user is a real person or an automated entity.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The algorithm reportedly uses machine learning to optimize the process.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Through a contract with the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency, Cloudflare provides registry and authoritative DNS services to the .gov top-level domain.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare also launched Cloudflare for Campaigns in 2020, to offer free cybersecurity tools to political campaigns.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Those tools expanded to include secure email systems in 2025.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In November 2020, Cloudflare announced Cloudflare for Teams, consisting of a DNS resolver and web gateway called "Gateway", and a zero-trust authentication service called "Access".
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare released an Oblivious HTTP relay service in 2022, called Privacy Gateway.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare announced a partnership with PhonePe in January 2023 to secure its mobile payment system.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In February, Cloudflare launched Wildebeest to allow Mastodon users to set up and run their own instances on Cloudflare's infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In August 2023, Cloudflare started the Project Cybersafe Schools program as part of a $20 million grant program from Amazon Web Services, making 70 percent of public school districts in the United States eligible for no-cost cybersecurity services.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In March 2024, it announced Firewall for AI to defend applications running large language models (LLMs).
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In September, Cloudflare announced Ephemeral IDs, which identifies fraudulent activity by linking behavior to a client through a short-lived, generated ID, rather than the traditional means of using an IP address.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The same month, the company also announced all ISP and equipment manufacturers could use its DNS resolvers for free.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare introduced the Cloudforce One threat events platform in March 2025, offering real-time insights into cyberattacks using data gathered from Cloudflare's network.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare's overarching secure access service edge (SASE) platform debuted in October 2020.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare announced the acquisition of Area 1 Security in February 2022, a company who developed a product designed to combat phishing email attacks.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare acquired Nefeli Networks in March 2024, a cloud networking company, co-founded by computer scientist Sylvia Ratnasamy.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2019, Cloudflare released a VPN-like service called WARP, and open sourced the custom underlying WireGuard implementation written in Rust.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In January 2021, the company began providing its "Waiting Room" digital queue product for free for COVID-19 vaccination scheduling under the title "Project Fair Shot".
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Project Fair Shot later won a Webby People's Choice Award in 2022 for Event Management under the Apps & Software category.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In March 2023, Cloudflare announced post-quantum cryptography will be made freely and forever available to cloud services, applications and Internet connections.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare released the Speed Brain and Instant Purge features in September 2024, to significantly reduce page load latency by prefetching content, and invalidating cached content in under 150ms.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2024, Cloudflare announced plans to launch a new payment method, called Stripe Link, which went into beta in the fall.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Since 2010, Cloudflare has collaborated with the National Center for Missing & Exploited Children to provide data, files, and supplemental investigation from abuse reports observed on its network.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare designed a new NCMEC reporting system in 2024, updating it in 2025 by integrating Cloudflare Workflows and making the CSAM scanning tool accessible globally.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] On June 1, 2012, the hacker group UGNazi compromised some of Cloudflare CEO Matthew Prince's accounts and redirected visitors of the website 4chan to a Twitter account belonging to UGNazi.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] They allegedly used social engineering to trick AT&T support staff into giving them access to Prince's voicemail, then exploited a vulnerability in Cloudflare's use of Google's two-factor authentication system.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Once in control of Prince's email account, UGNazi was able to redirect the 4chan domain through Cloudflare's database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] From September 2016 until February 2017, a Cloudflare bug nicknamed Cloudbleed leaked sensitive data, including passwords and authentication tokens, from customer websites by sending extra data in response to web requests.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] On November 18, 2025, Cloudflare suffered a major global outage that caused widespread 500 errors, slowing down many platforms, making them unreachable or completely down for users around the world.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Access to WARP, Cloudflare's VPN service, was also briefly disabled in London.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] During the outage, a spokesperson for Cloudflare said the company had seen a "spike in unusual traffic", causing some traffic passing through its network to experience errors.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] At 14:23 UTC, *The Guardian* reported that Cloudflare had released a fix.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] It also reported that maintenance was due at various locations, though this is not known to have caused the outages.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] At 14:42 UTC, Cloudflare informed users on its status page that the fix had been implemented and that it would take some time for remaining post-deployment issues to be fixed.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] A technical postmortem of the incident was released the day following the outage.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare attributed the outage to a change in the configuration of a database, which caused an invalid file to be sent to all servers on the network.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] On December 5, Cloudflare suffered another global outage, which began at 09:00 AM UTC.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] This was the second such outage in three weeks to affect Cloudflare's services.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In January 2026, security researchers disclosed a vulnerability in Cloudflare's Web application firewall (WAF) that allowed attackers to bypass security rules and access origin servers directly.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The flaw existed in the handling of ACME challenge requests; the logic disabled WAF protections for requests targeting the `/.well-known/acme-challenge/` path without sufficiently verifying if the token matched an active validation attempt.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare patched the vulnerability in October 2025, stating that the issue was a logic flaw rather than a code execution vulnerability and that there was no evidence of exploitation.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare has established a content neutrality policy and opposes the policing of its customers on the basis of free speech unless said customers break the law.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The company has faced criticism for not banning hate speech websites and websites allegedly connected to terrorism groups.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare has maintained that no law enforcement agency has asked the company to discontinue these services and it closely monitors its obligations under U.S. laws.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2022, a research paper by Stanford University found that Cloudflare was a prominent CDN provider, among several other providers, that are disproportionately responsible for serving misinformation websites.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare has come under pressure due to its services being utilized to access far-right content.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare provided DNS routing and DDoS protection for the white supremacist and neo-Nazi website *The Daily Stormer*.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2017, after previously refusing to take any action against the website, Cloudflare stopped providing its services to *The Daily Stormer* after an announcement on the website asserted that Cloudflare executives were privately supporting its ideology.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] As a self-described "free speech absolutist", Prince claimed he did not want to repeat the decision, and sought out protections for the company should they be faced with a similar situation in the future.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Prince further addressed the dangers of large companies deciding what is allowed to stay online, a concern shared by a number of civil liberties groups and privacy experts.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The Electronic Frontier Foundation, a US digital rights group, said that services such as Cloudflare should not be deciding what speech is acceptable and that illegal content should be handled through the legal system.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2019, Cloudflare was criticized for providing services to the far-right discussion and imageboard 8chan.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The message board has been linked to mass shootings in the United States and the Christchurch mosque shootings in New Zealand.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In addition, a number of news organizations including *The Washington Post* and *The Daily Dot* have reported on the existence of child pornography and child sexual abuse discussion boards.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] A Cloudflare representative said that the platform "does not host the referenced websites, cannot block websites, and is not in the business of hiding companies that host illegal content".
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare did not terminate service to 8chan until public and legal pressure mounted in the wake of the 2019 El Paso shooting, in which the associated manifesto was published to 8chan.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In an interview with *The Guardian* immediately after the shooting, CEO Matthew Prince defended Cloudflare's support of 8chan, saying that he had a "moral obligation" to keep 8chan online.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] On August 5, 2019, two days after Prince's interview with The Guardian, Cloudflare terminated service to 8chan.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare explained that 8chan "have proven themselves to be lawless and that lawlessness has caused multiple tragic deaths.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare provided DDoS mitigation and acted as a reverse proxy for Kiwi Farms.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The site often engages in harassment and doxxing of targets and has been implicated in the suicides of at least three people.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Kiwi Farms also has a reputation for transphobic content, and its users have been accused of swatting vulnerable individuals.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Although Cloudflare was not the primary website host, it did perform critical services to keep Kiwi Farms on-line, both protecting the site from denial-of-service attacks and optimizing content delivery.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2022, a campaign was launched by transgender activist Clara Sorrenti, who has previously been targeted by the forum, to pressure Cloudflare into terminating service for Kiwi Farms.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare responded by issuing a statement on its abuse policies and saying it didn't want to set precedent for speech on the internet with its "extraordinary" decision.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The company also released a blog post and likened its services to that of a public utility, emphasizing that it does not believe in shutting down security services based on content it finds objectionable.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] They acknowledged that while it might be more popular to remove sites that the Cloudflare team finds offensive, it stood by its decision not to do so.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The company also defended its decision by saying that it donated all earnings from anti-LGBTIQ+ sites to an organization that advocated for LGBTIQ+ rights.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] On September 3, 2022, Cloudflare blocked Kiwi Farms, citing urgent escalating rhetoric against targets of Kiwi Farms, stating that there is an "unprecedented emergency and immediate threat to human life".
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Switter was a social media network for the sex worker community, built by Australia-based company Assembly Four on Mastodon's open-source software, before Cloudflare dropped Switter as a client and ceased services in April 2018, citing terms of service violations.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] This occurred shortly after the passage of FOSTA/SESTA, a set of bills criminalizing websites that facilitate or support sex trafficking in 2018.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] SESTA weakened protections for Internet infrastructure companies and was criticized on free speech grounds due to concerns about disproportionate impact and disruptions to the lives of sex workers.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare said the move was "related to our attempts to understand FOSTA, which is a very bad law and [sets] a very dangerous precedent".
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Assembly Four said that "Given Cloudflare's previous stances of privacy and freedom, as well as fighting alongside the EFF, we had hoped they would take a stand against FOSTA/SESTA".
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2015, testimony to the United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs, it was reported that two of the top three online chat forums and nearly forty other web sites belonging to the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL) were guarded by Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare has been cited in reports by The Spamhaus Project, an international spam tracking organization, for the high numbers of cybercriminal botnet operations hosted by Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] An October 2015 report found that Cloudflare provisioned 40% of the SSL certificates used by typosquatting phishing sites, which use deceptive domain names resembling those of banks and payment processors to compromise Internet users' banking and other transactions.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare has been criticized for having a conflict of interest by providing DDoS protection to both the operators and victims of "stresser" services.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2018, Cloudflare was identified by the European Union's Counterfeit and Piracy Watch List as a "notorious market" which engages in, facilitates, or benefits from counterfeiting and piracy.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The report noted that Cloudflare hides and anonymizes the operators of 40% of the world's pirate sites, and 62% of the 500 largest such sites, and "does not follow due diligence when opening accounts for websites to prevent illegal sites from using its services".
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2020, an Italian court ruled Cloudflare had to block current and future domain names and IP addresses of the pirate IPTV service "IPTV THE BEST" for infringing on Lega Serie A intellectual property.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] At the time, Cloudflare was already blocking 22 domain names in Italy.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Following the December 2024 court ruling, the Spanish LaLiga requested that telephone operators block Cloudflare's IP address ranges in February 2025.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare hosted websites that illegally broadcast soccer matches.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] As a result, the pirate platform DuckVision was shut down before the derby between Real Madrid and Atlético Madrid.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The platform had 200,000 users and was backed by Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] The blocks affected major legitimate websites, including X, Vimeo, Steam, GitHub, and the Royal Spanish Academy.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare CEO Matthew Prince responded that the company decided to remain providing services to Russian people to counter Russia's attempts to raise a 'digital iron curtain'.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] Cloudflare's Project Galileo, launched in 2014, offers DDoS protection to NGOs for free.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2022, they extended free protection to Ukrainian government and telecoms.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] In 2022, Japanese publishers Shueisha, Kodansha, Shogakukan, and Kadokawa Shoten filed a copyright lawsuit against Cloudflare, alleging that the service was distributing data to manga piracy sites and sought an injunction and ¥460 million (US$4 million) in damages.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] On November 19, 2025, a judge ruled in favor of the publishers.
[src:cloudflare-d1/cloudflare] While the ruling recognized approximately ¥3.6 billion (US$24 million) in damages, Cloudflare was ordered to pay a total amount of ¥500 million (US$3.6 million), as the publishers claimed that Cloudflare was only partially responsible for the damages.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] In computing, a **database** is an organized collection of data or a type of data store based on the use of a **database management system** (**DBMS**), the software that interacts with end users, applications, and the database itself to capture and analyze the data.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The DBMS additionally encompasses the core facilities provided to administer the database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The sum total of the database, the DBMS and the associated applications can be referred to as a **database system**.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Often the term "database" is also used loosely to refer to any of the DBMS, the database system or an application associated with the database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Professional book indexers used index cards in the creation of book indexes until they were replaced by indexing software in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Small databases can be stored on a file system, while large databases are hosted on computer clusters or cloud storage.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The design of databases spans formal techniques and practical considerations, including data modeling, efficient data representation and storage, query languages, security and privacy of sensitive data, and distributed computing issues, including supporting concurrent access and fault tolerance.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Computer scientists may classify database management systems according to the database models that they support.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Relational databases became dominant in the 1980s.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] These model data as rows and columns in a series of tables, and the vast majority use SQL for writing and querying data.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] In the 2000s, non-relational databases became popular, collectively referred to as NoSQL, because they use different query languages.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The DBMS provides various functions that allow entry, storage and retrieval of large quantities of information and provides ways to manage how that information is organized.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Because of the close relationship between them, the term "database" is often used casually to refer to both a database and the DBMS used to manipulate it.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Outside the world of professional information technology, the term *database* is often used to refer to any collection of related data (such as a spreadsheet or a card index) as size and usage requirements typically necessitate use of a database management system.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Both a database and its DBMS conform to the principles of a particular database model.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] "Database system" refers collectively to the database model, database management system, and database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Physically, database servers are dedicated computers that hold the actual databases and run only the DBMS and related software.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Database servers are usually multiprocessor computers, with generous memory and RAID disk arrays used for stable storage.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Hardware database accelerators, connected to one or more servers via a high-speed channel, are also used in large-volume transaction processing environments.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] DBMSs are found at the heart of most database applications.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] DBMSs may be built around a custom multitasking kernel with built-in networking support, but modern DBMSs typically rely on a standard operating system to provide these functions.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Since DBMSs comprise a significant market, computer and storage vendors often take into account DBMS requirements in their own development plans.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The sizes, capabilities, and performance of databases and their respective DBMSs have grown in orders of magnitude.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] These performance increases were enabled by the technology progress in the areas of processors, computer memory, computer storage, and computer networks.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The concept of a database was made possible by the emergence of direct access storage media such as magnetic disks, which became widely available in the mid-1960s; earlier systems relied on sequential storage of data on magnetic tape.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The subsequent development of database technology can be divided into three eras based on data model or structure: navigational, SQL/relational, and post-relational.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The two main early navigational data models were the hierarchical model and the CODASYL model (network model).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] These were characterized by the use of pointers (often physical disk addresses) to follow relationships from one record to another.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The relational model, first proposed in 1970 by Edgar F.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Codd, departed from this tradition by insisting that applications should search for data by content, rather than by following links.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The relational model employs sets of ledger-style tables, each used for a different type of entity.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Only in the mid-1980s did computing hardware become powerful enough to allow the wide deployment of relational systems (DBMSs plus applications).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] By the early 1990s, however, relational systems dominated in all large-scale data processing applications, and as of 2018 they remain dominant: IBM Db2, Oracle, MySQL, and Microsoft SQL Server are the most searched DBMS.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The dominant database language, standardized SQL for the relational model, has influenced database languages for other data models.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Object databases were developed in the 1980s to overcome the inconvenience of object–relational impedance mismatch, which led to the coining of the term "post-relational" and also the development of hybrid object–relational databases.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The next generation of post-relational databases in the late 2000s became known as NoSQL databases, introducing fast key–value stores and document-oriented databases.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] A competing "next generation" known as NewSQL databases attempted new implementations that retained the relational/SQL model while aiming to match the high performance of NoSQL compared to commercially available relational DBMSs.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The introduction of the term *database* coincided with the availability of direct-access storage (disks and drums) from the mid-1960s onwards.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The term represented a contrast with the tape-based systems of the past, allowing shared interactive use rather than daily batch processing.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The Oxford English Dictionary cites a 1962 report by the System Development Corporation of California as the first to use the term "data-base" in a specific technical sense.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] As computers grew in speed and capability, a number of general-purpose database systems emerged; by the mid-1960s a number of such systems had come into commercial use.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Interest in a standard began to grow, and Charles Bachman, author of one such product, the Integrated Data Store (IDS), founded the Database Task Group within CODASYL, the group responsible for the creation and standardization of COBOL.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] In 1971, the Database Task Group delivered their standard, which generally became known as the *CODASYL approach*, and soon a number of commercial products based on this approach entered the market.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The CODASYL approach offered applications the ability to navigate around a linked data set which was formed into a large network.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Later systems added B-trees to provide alternate access paths.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Many CODASYL databases also added a declarative query language for end users (as distinct from the navigational API).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] However, CODASYL databases were complex and required significant training and effort to produce useful applications.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] IBM also had its own DBMS in 1966, known as Information Management System (IMS).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] IMS was a development of software written for the Apollo program on the System/360.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] IMS was generally similar in concept to CODASYL, but used a strict hierarchy for its model of data navigation instead of CODASYL's network model.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Both concepts later became known as navigational databases due to the way data was accessed: the term was popularized by Bachman's 1973 Turing Award presentation *The Programmer as Navigator*.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] IMS is classified by IBM as a hierarchical database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] IDMS and Cincom Systems' TOTAL databases are classified as network databases.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Codd worked at IBM in San Jose, California, in an office primarily involved in the development of hard disk systems.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] He was unhappy with the navigational model of the CODASYL approach, notably the lack of a "search" facility.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] In 1970, he wrote a number of papers that outlined a new approach to database construction that eventually culminated in the groundbreaking *A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks*.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The paper described a new system for storing and working with large databases.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Instead of records being stored in some sort of linked list of free-form records as in CODASYL, Codd's idea was to organize the data as a number of "tables", each table being used for a different type of entity.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Each table would contain a fixed number of columns containing the attributes of the entity.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Splitting the data into a set of normalized tables (or *relations*) aimed to ensure that each "fact" was only stored once, thus simplifying update operations.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Virtual tables called *views* could present the data in different ways for different users, but views could not be directly updated.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Codd used mathematical terms to define the model: relations, tuples, and domains rather than tables, rows, and columns.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The terminology that is now familiar came from early implementations.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Codd would later criticize the tendency for practical implementations to depart from the mathematical foundations on which the model was based.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The use of primary keys (user-oriented identifiers) to represent cross-table relationships, rather than disk addresses, had two primary motivations.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] From an engineering perspective, it enabled tables to be relocated and resized without expensive database reorganization.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] There is no loss of expressiveness compared with the hierarchic or network models, though the connections between tables are no longer so explicit.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] In the hierarchic and network models, records were allowed to have a complex internal structure.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] For example, the salary history of an employee might be represented as a "repeating group" within the employee record.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] In the relational model, the process of normalization led to such internal structures being replaced by data held in multiple tables, connected only by logical keys.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] For instance, a common use of a database system is to track information about users, their name, login information, various addresses and phone numbers.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] In the navigational approach, all of this data would be placed in a single variable-length record.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] In the relational approach, the data would be *normalized* into a user table, an address table and a phone number table (for instance).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Records would be created in these optional tables only if the address or phone numbers were actually provided.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] As well as identifying rows/records using logical identifiers rather than disk addresses, Codd changed the way in which applications assembled data from multiple records.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Rather than requiring applications to gather data one record at a time by navigating the links, they would use a declarative query language that expressed what data was required, rather than the access path by which it should be found.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Finding an efficient access path to the data became the responsibility of the database management system, rather than the application programmer.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] This process, called query optimization, depended on the fact that queries were expressed in terms of mathematical logic.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Beginning in 1973, INGRES delivered its first test products which were generally ready for widespread use in 1979.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] INGRES was similar to System R in a number of ways, including the use of a "language" for data access, known as QUEL.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Over time, INGRES moved to the emerging SQL standard.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] IBM itself did one test implementation of the relational model, PRTV, and a production one, Business System 12, both now discontinued.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Honeywell wrote MRDS for Multics, and now there are two new implementations: Alphora Dataphor and Rel.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Most other DBMS implementations usually called *relational* are actually SQL DBMSs.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] In 1970, the University of Michigan began development of the MICRO Information Management System based on D.L.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The university in 1974 hosted a debate between Codd and Bachman which Bruce Lindsay of IBM later described as "throwing lightning bolts at each other!".
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] MICRO was used to manage very large data sets by the US Department of Labor, the U.S.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Environmental Protection Agency, and researchers from the University of Alberta, the University of Michigan, and Wayne State University.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] It ran on IBM mainframe computers using the Michigan Terminal System.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The system remained in production until 1998.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] In the 1970s and 1980s, attempts were made to build database systems with integrated hardware and software.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The underlying philosophy was that such integration would provide higher performance at a lower cost.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Examples were IBM System/38, the early offering of Teradata, and the Britton Lee, Inc. database machine.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Another approach to hardware support for database management was ICL's CAFS accelerator, a hardware disk controller with programmable search capabilities.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] In the long term, these efforts were generally unsuccessful because specialized database machines could not keep pace with the rapid development and progress of general-purpose computers.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Thus most database systems nowadays are software systems running on general-purpose hardware, using general-purpose computer data storage.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] However, this idea is still pursued in certain applications by some companies like Netezza and Oracle (Exadata).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] IBM formed a team led by Codd that started working on a prototype system, *System R* despite opposition from others at the company.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The first version was ready in 1974/5, and work then started on multi-table systems in which the data could be split so that all of the data for a record (some of which is optional) did not have to be stored in a single large "chunk".
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Subsequent multi-user versions were tested by customers in 1978 and 1979, by which time a standardized query language – SQL – had been added.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Codd's ideas were establishing themselves as both workable and superior to CODASYL, pushing IBM to develop a true production version of System R, known as *SQL/DS*, and, later, *Database 2* (IBM Db2).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Larry Ellison's Oracle Database (or more simply, Oracle) started from a different chain, based on IBM's papers on System R.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Though Oracle V1 implementations were completed in 1978, it was not until Oracle Version 2 when Ellison beat IBM to market in 1979.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Stonebraker went on to apply the lessons from INGRES to develop a new database, Postgres, which is now known as PostgreSQL.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] PostgreSQL is often used for global mission-critical applications (the .org and .info domain name registries use it as their primary data store, as do many large companies and financial institutions).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] In Sweden, Codd's paper was also read and Mimer SQL was developed in the mid-1970s at Uppsala University.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] In 1984, this project was consolidated into an independent enterprise.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Another data model, the entity–relationship model, emerged in 1976 and gained popularity for database design as it emphasized a more familiar description than the earlier relational model.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Later on, entity–relationship constructs were retrofitted as a data modeling construct for the relational model, and the difference between the two has become irrelevant.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Besides IBM and various software companies such as Sybase and Informix Corporation, most large computer hardware vendors by the 1980s had their own database systems such as DEC's VAX Rdb/VMS.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The decade ushered in the age of desktop computing.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The new computers empowered their users with spreadsheets like Lotus 1-2-3 and database software like dBASE.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The dBASE product was lightweight and easy for any computer user to understand out of the box.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Wayne Ratliff, the creator of dBASE, stated: "dBASE was different from programs like BASIC, C, FORTRAN, and COBOL in that a lot of the dirty work had already been done.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] By the start of the decade databases had become a billion-dollar industry in about ten years.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The 1990s, along with a rise in object-oriented programming, saw a growth in how data in various databases were handled.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Programmers and designers began to treat the data in their databases as objects.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] That is to say that if a person's data were in a database, that person's attributes, such as their address, phone number, and age, were now considered to belong to that person instead of being extraneous data.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] This allows for relations between data to be related to objects and their attributes and not to individual fields.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The term "object–relational impedance mismatch" described the inconvenience of translating between programmed objects and database tables.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Object databases and object–relational databases attempt to solve this problem by providing an object-oriented language (sometimes as extensions to SQL) that programmers can use as alternative to purely relational SQL.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] On the programming side, libraries known as object–relational mappings (ORMs) attempt to solve the same problem.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Database sales grew rapidly during the dotcom bubble and, after its end, the rise of ecommerce.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The popularity of open source databases such as MySQL has grown since 2000, to the extent that Ken Jacobs of Oracle said in 2005 that perhaps "these guys are doing to us what we did to IBM".
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] XML databases are a type of structured document-oriented database that allows querying based on XML document attributes.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] XML databases are mostly used in applications where the data is conveniently viewed as a collection of documents, with a structure that can vary from the very flexible to the highly rigid: examples include scientific articles, patents, tax filings, and personnel records.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] NoSQL databases are often very fast, do not require fixed table schemas, avoid join operations by storing denormalized data, and are designed to scale horizontally.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Some NoSQL databases, including graph databases such as Neo4j, represent data as nodes and edges to model relationships between entities.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] In recent years, there has been a strong demand for massively distributed databases with high partition tolerance, but according to the CAP theorem, it is impossible for a distributed system to simultaneously provide consistency, availability, and partition tolerance guarantees.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] A distributed system can satisfy any two of these guarantees at the same time, but not all three.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] For that reason, many NoSQL databases are using what is called eventual consistency to provide both availability and partition tolerance guarantees with a reduced level of data consistency.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] NewSQL is a class of modern relational databases that aims to provide the same scalable performance of NoSQL systems for online transaction processing (read-write) workloads while still using SQL and maintaining the ACID guarantees of a traditional database system.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Databases are used to support internal operations of organizations and to underpin online interactions with customers and suppliers (see Enterprise software).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Databases are used to hold administrative information and more specialized data, such as engineering data or economic models.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Examples include computerized library systems, flight reservation systems, computerized parts inventory systems, and many content management systems that store websites as collections of webpages in a database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] One way to classify databases involves the type of their contents, for example: bibliographic, document-text, statistical, or multimedia objects.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Another way is by their application area, for example: accounting, music compositions, movies, banking, manufacturing, or insurance.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] A third way is by some technical aspect, such as the database structure or interface type.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] This section lists a few of the adjectives used to characterize different kinds of databases.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database." Examples of DBMS's include MySQL, MariaDB, PostgreSQL, Microsoft SQL Server, Oracle Database, and Microsoft Access.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The DBMS acronym is sometimes extended to indicate the underlying database model, with RDBMS for the relational, OODBMS for the object (oriented) and ORDBMS for the object–relational model.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Other extensions can indicate some other characteristics, such as DDBMS for a distributed database management systems.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The functionality provided by a DBMS can vary enormously.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The core functionality is the storage, retrieval and update of data.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] It is also generally to be expected the DBMS will provide a set of utilities for such purposes as may be necessary to administer the database effectively, including import, export, monitoring, defragmentation and analysis utilities.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The core part of the DBMS interacting between the database and the application interface sometimes referred to as the database engine.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Often DBMSs will have configuration parameters that can be statically and dynamically tuned, for example the maximum amount of main memory on a server the database can use.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The trend is to minimize the amount of manual configuration, and for cases such as embedded databases the need to target zero-administration is paramount.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The large major enterprise DBMSs have tended to increase in size and functionality and have involved up to thousands of human years of development effort throughout their lifetime.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Early multi-user DBMS typically only allowed for the application to reside on the same computer with access via terminals or terminal emulation software.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The client–server architecture was a development where the application resided on a client desktop and the database on a server allowing the processing to be distributed.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] This evolved into a multitier architecture incorporating application servers and web servers with the end user interface via a web browser with the database only directly connected to the adjacent tier.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] A general-purpose DBMS will provide public application programming interfaces (API) and optionally a processor for database languages such as SQL to allow applications to be written to interact with and manipulate the database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] A special purpose DBMS may use a private API and be specifically customized and linked to a single application.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] For example, an email system performs many of the functions of a general-purpose DBMS such as message insertion, message deletion, attachment handling, blocklist lookup, associating messages an email address and so forth however these functions are limited to what is required to handle email.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] External interaction with the database will be via an application program that interfaces with the DBMS.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] This can range from a database tool that allows users to execute SQL queries textually or graphically, to a website that happens to use a database to store and search information.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] A programmer will code interactions to the database (sometimes referred to as a datasource) via an application program interface (API) or via a database language.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The particular API or language chosen will need to be supported by DBMS, possibly indirectly via a preprocessor or a bridging API.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Some API's aim to be database independent, ODBC being a commonly known example.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Other common API's include JDBC and ADO.NET.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Database languages are specific to a particular data model.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Database storage is the container of the physical materialization of a database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] It comprises the *internal* (physical) *level* in the database architecture.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] It also contains all the information needed (e.g., metadata, "data about the data", and internal data structures) to reconstruct the *conceptual level* and *external level* from the internal level when needed.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Databases as digital objects contain three layers of information which must be stored: the data, the structure, and the semantics.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Proper storage of all three layers is needed for future preservation and longevity of the database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Putting data into permanent storage is generally the responsibility of the database engine a.k.a.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] A DBMS, while in operation, always has its database residing in several types of storage (e.g., memory and external storage).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The database data and the additional needed information, possibly in very large amounts, are coded into bits.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Some DBMSs support specifying which character encoding was used to store data, so multiple encodings can be used in the same database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Various low-level database storage structures are used by the storage engine to serialize the data model so it can be written to the medium of choice.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Techniques such as indexing may be used to improve performance.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Conventional storage is row-oriented, but there are also column-oriented and correlation databases.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Often storage redundancy is employed to increase performance.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] A common example is storing *materialized views*, which consist of frequently needed *external views* or query results.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Storing such views saves the expensive computing them each time they are needed.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The downsides of materialized views are the overhead incurred when updating them to keep them synchronized with their original updated database data, and the cost of storage redundancy.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Updates of a replicated object need to be synchronized across the object copies.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] In many cases, the entire database is replicated.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] With data virtualization, the data used remains in its original locations and real-time access is established to allow analytics across multiple sources.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] This can aid in resolving some technical difficulties such as compatibility problems when combining data from various platforms, lowering the risk of error caused by faulty data, and guaranteeing that the newest data is used.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Furthermore, avoiding the creation of a new database containing personal information can make it easier to comply with privacy regulations.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] However, with data virtualization, the connection to all necessary data sources must be operational as there is no local copy of the data, which is one of the main drawbacks of the approach.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Database security deals with all various aspects of protecting the database content, its owners, and its users.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] It ranges from protection from intentional unauthorized database uses to unintentional database accesses by unauthorized entities (e.g., a person or a computer program).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Database access control deals with controlling who (a person or a certain computer program) are allowed to access what information in the database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Database access controls are set by special authorized (by the database owner) personnel that uses dedicated protected security DBMS interfaces.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] This may be managed directly on an individual basis, or by the assignment of individuals and privileges to groups, or (in the most elaborate models) through the assignment of individuals and groups to roles which are then granted entitlements.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Data security prevents unauthorized users from viewing or updating the database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Using passwords, users are allowed access to the entire database or subsets of it called "subschemas".
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] For example, an employee database can contain all the data about an individual employee, but one group of users may be authorized to view only payroll data, while others are allowed access to only work history and medical data.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] If the DBMS provides a way to interactively enter and update the database, as well as interrogate it, this capability allows for managing personal databases.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Change and access logging records who accessed which attributes, what was changed, and when it was changed.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Logging services allow for a forensic database audit later by keeping a record of access occurrences and changes.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Sometimes application-level code is used to record changes rather than leaving this in the database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Monitoring can be set up to attempt to detect security breaches.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Therefore, organizations must take database security seriously because of the many benefits it provides.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Organizations will be safeguarded from security breaches and hacking activities like firewall intrusion, virus spread, and ransom ware.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] This helps in protecting the company's essential information, which cannot be shared with outsiders at any cause.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Database transactions can be used to introduce some level of fault tolerance and data integrity after recovery from a crash.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] A database transaction is a unit of work, typically encapsulating a number of operations over a database (e.g., reading a database object, writing, acquiring or releasing a lock, etc.), an abstraction supported in database and also other systems.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Each transaction has well defined boundaries in terms of which program/code executions are included in that transaction (determined by the transaction's programmer via special transaction commands).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The acronym ACID describes some ideal properties of a database transaction: atomicity, consistency, isolation, and durability.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] A database built with one DBMS is not portable to another DBMS (i.e., the other DBMS cannot run it).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] However, in some situations, it is desirable to migrate a database from one DBMS to another.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The reasons are primarily economical (different DBMSs may have different total costs of ownership or TCOs), functional, and operational (different DBMSs may have different capabilities).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The migration involves the database's transformation from one DBMS type to another.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] The transformation should maintain (if possible) the database related application (i.e., all related application programs) intact.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Thus, the database's conceptual and external architectural levels should be maintained in the transformation.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] It may be desired that also some aspects of the architecture internal level are maintained.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] A complex or large database migration may be a complicated and costly (one-time) project by itself, which should be factored into the decision to migrate.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] This is in spite of the fact that tools may exist to help migration between specific DBMSs.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Typically, a DBMS vendor provides tools to help import databases from other popular DBMSs.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] After designing a database for an application, the next stage is building the database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Typically, an appropriate general-purpose DBMS can be selected to be used for this purpose.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] A DBMS provides the needed user interfaces to be used by database administrators to define the needed application's data structures within the DBMS's respective data model.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Other user interfaces are used to select needed DBMS parameters (like security related, storage allocation parameters, etc.).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] In some cases, the database becomes operational while empty of application data, and data are accumulated during its operation.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] After the database is created, initialized and populated it needs to be maintained.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Various database parameters may need changing and the database may need to be tuned (tuning) for better performance; application's data structures may be changed or added, new related application programs may be written to add to the application's functionality, etc.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] Sometimes it is desired to bring a database back to a previous state (for many reasons, e.g., cases when the database is found corrupted due to a software error, or if it has been updated with erroneous data).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] To achieve this, a backup operation is done occasionally or continuously, where each desired database state (i.e., the values of its data and their embedding in database's data structures) is kept within dedicated backup files (many techniques exist to do this effectively).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p01] When it is decided by a database administrator to bring the database back to this state (e.g., by specifying this state by a desired point in time when the database was in this state), these files are used to restore that state.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] Static analysis techniques for software verification can be applied also in the scenario of query languages.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] In particular, the *Abstract interpretation framework has been extended to the field of query languages for relational databases as a way to support sound approximation techniques.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] The semantics of query languages can be tuned according to suitable abstractions of the concrete domain of data.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] The abstraction of relational database systems has many interesting applications, in particular, for security purposes, such as fine-grained access control, watermarking, etc.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] Increasingly, there are calls for a single system that incorporates all of these core functionalities into the same build, test, and deployment framework for database management and source control.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] Borrowing from other developments in the software industry, some market such offerings as "DevOps for database".
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] The first task of a database designer is to produce a conceptual data model that reflects the structure of the information to be held in the database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] A common approach to this is to develop an entity–relationship model, often with the aid of drawing tools.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] Another popular approach is the Unified Modeling Language.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] A successful data model will accurately reflect the possible state of the external world being modeled: for example, if people can have more than one phone number, it will allow this information to be captured.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] The answers to these questions establish definitions of the terminology used for entities (customers, products, flights, flight segments) and their relationships and attributes.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] Producing the conceptual data model sometimes involves input from business processes, or the analysis of workflow in the organization.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] This can help to establish what information is needed in the database, and what can be left out.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] For example, it can help when deciding whether the database needs to hold historic data as well as current data.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] Having produced a conceptual data model that users are happy with, the next stage is to translate this into a schema that implements the relevant data structures within the database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] This process is often called logical database design, and the output is a logical data model expressed in the form of a schema.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] Whereas the conceptual data model is (in theory at least) independent of the choice of database technology, the logical data model will be expressed in terms of a particular database model supported by the chosen DBMS.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] (The terms *data model* and *database model* are often used interchangeably, but in this article we use *data model* for the design of a specific database, and *database model* for the modeling notation used to express that design).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] The most popular database model for general-purpose databases is the relational model, or more precisely, the relational model as represented by the SQL language.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] The process of creating a logical database design using this model uses a methodical approach known as normalization.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] The goal of normalization is to ensure that each elementary "fact" is only recorded in one place, so that insertions, updates, and deletions automatically maintain consistency.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] The final stage of database design is to make the decisions that affect performance, scalability, recovery, security, and the like, which depend on the particular DBMS.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] This is often called *physical database design*, and the output is the physical data model.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] A key goal during this stage is data independence, meaning that the decisions made for performance optimization purposes should be invisible to end-users and applications.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] There are two types of data independence: Physical data independence and logical data independence.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] Physical design is driven mainly by performance requirements, and requires a good knowledge of the expected workload and access patterns, and a deep understanding of the features offered by the chosen DBMS.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] Another aspect of physical database design is security.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] It involves both defining access control to database objects as well as defining security levels and methods for the data itself.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] A database model is a type of data model that determines the logical structure of a database and fundamentally determines in which manner data can be stored, organized, and manipulated.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] The most popular example of a database model is the relational model (or the SQL approximation of relational), which uses a table-based format.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] An object–relational database combines the two related structures.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] While there is typically only one conceptual and internal view of the data, there can be any number of different external views.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] This allows users to see database information in a more business-related way rather than from a technical, processing viewpoint.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] For example, a financial department of a company needs the payment details of all employees as part of the company's expenses, but does not need details about employees that are in the interest of the human resources department.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] Thus different departments need different *views* of the company's database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] The three-level database architecture relates to the concept of *data independence* which was one of the major initial driving forces of the relational model.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] The idea is that changes made at a certain level do not affect the view at a higher level.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] For example, changes in the internal level do not affect application programs written using conceptual level interfaces, which reduces the impact of making physical changes to improve performance.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] The conceptual view provides a level of indirection between internal and external.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] On the one hand it provides a common view of the database, independent of different external view structures, and on the other hand it abstracts away details of how the data are stored or managed (internal level).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] In principle every level, and even every external view, can be presented by a different data model.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] In practice usually a given DBMS uses the same data model for both the external and the conceptual levels (e.g., relational model).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] The internal level, which is hidden inside the DBMS and depends on its implementation, requires a different level of detail and uses its own types of data structure types.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] Database technology has been an active research topic since the 1960s, both in academia and in the research and development groups of companies (for example IBM Research).
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] Research activity includes theory and development of prototypes.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] Notable research topics have included models, the atomic transaction concept, related concurrency control techniques, query languages and query optimization methods, RAID, and more.
[src:cloudflare-d1/database-p02] The database research area has several dedicated academic journals (for example, *ACM Transactions on Database Systems*-TODS, *Data and Knowledge Engineering*-DKE) and annual conferences (e.g., ACM SIGMOD, ACM PODS, VLDB, IEEE ICDE).
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] The term began being used in the 1990s to describe content delivery networks—these were used to deliver website and video content from servers located near users.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] In the early 2000s, these systems expanded their scope to hosting other applications, leading to early edge computing services.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] These services could do things like find dealers, manage shopping carts, gather real-time data, and place ads.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] The Internet of things (IoT), where devices are connected to the Internet, is often linked with edge computing.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Edge computing involves running computer programs that deliver quick responses close to where requests are made.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Karim Arabi, during an IEEE DAC 2014 keynote and later at an MIT MTL Seminar in 2015, described edge computing as computing that occurs outside the cloud, at the network's edge, particularly for applications needing immediate data processing.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Edge computing is often equated with fog computing, particularly in smaller setups.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] However, in larger deployments, such as smart cities, fog computing serves as a distinct layer between edge computing and cloud computing, with each layer having its own responsibilities.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] "The State of the Edge" report explains that edge computing focuses on servers located close to the end-users.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Alex Reznik, Chair of the ETSI MEC ISG standards committee, defines 'edge' loosely as anything that's not a traditional data center.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] In cloud gaming, edge nodes, known as "gamelets", are typically within one or two network hops from the client, ensuring quick response times for real-time games.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Edge computing might use virtualization technology to simplify deploying and managing various applications on edge servers.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] In 2018, the world's data was expected to grow 61 percent to 175 zettabytes by 2025.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] According to research firm Gartner, around 10 percent of enterprise-generated data is created and processed outside a traditional centralized data center or cloud.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] By 2025, the firm predicts that this figure will reach 75 percent.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] The increase in IoT devices at the edge of the network is producing a massive amount of data — storing and using all that data in cloud data centers pushes network bandwidth requirements to the limit.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Despite the improvements in network technology, data centers cannot guarantee acceptable transfer rates and response times, which often is a critical requirement for many applications.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Furthermore, devices at the edge constantly consume data coming from the cloud, forcing companies to decentralize data storage and service provisioning, leveraging physical proximity to the end user.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] In a similar way, the aim of edge computing is to move the computation away from data centers towards the edge of the network, exploiting smart objects, mobile phones, or network gateways to perform tasks and provide services on behalf of the cloud.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] By moving services to the edge, it is possible to provide content caching, service delivery, persistent data storage, and IoT management resulting in better response times and transfer rates.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] At the same time, distributing the logic to different network nodes introduces new issues and challenges.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] The distributed nature of this paradigm introduces a shift in security schemes used in cloud computing.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] In edge computing, data may travel between different distributed nodes connected via the internet, and thus requires special encryption mechanisms independent of the cloud.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] This approach minimizes latency, reduces bandwidth consumption, and enhances real-time responsiveness for applications.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Edge nodes may also be resource-constrained devices, limiting the choice in terms of security methods.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Moreover, a shift from centralized top-down infrastructure to a decentralized trust model is required.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] On the other hand, by keeping and processing data at the edge, it is possible to increase privacy by minimizing the transmission of sensitive information to the cloud.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Furthermore, the ownership of collected data shifts from service providers to end-users.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Scalability in a distributed network must face different issues.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] First, it must take into account the heterogeneity of the devices, having different performance and energy constraints, the highly dynamic condition, and the reliability of the connections compared to more robust infrastructure of cloud data centers.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Moreover, security requirements may introduce further latency in the communication between nodes, which may slow down the scaling process.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] The state-of-the-art scheduling technique can increase the effective utilization of edge resources and scales the edge server by assigning minimum edge resources to each offloaded task.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Management of failovers is crucial in order to keep a service alive.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] If a single node goes down and is unreachable, users should still be able to access a service without interruptions.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Moreover, edge computing systems must provide actions to recover from a failure and alert the user about the incident.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] To this aim, each device must maintain the network topology of the entire distributed system, so that detection of errors and recovery become easily applicable.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Other factors that may influence this aspect are the connection technologies in use, which may provide different levels of reliability, and the accuracy of the data produced at the edge that could be unreliable due to particular environment conditions.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] As an example, an edge computing device, such as a voice assistant, may continue to provide service to local users even during cloud service or internet outages.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Edge computing brings analytical computational resources close to the end users and therefore can increase the responsiveness and throughput of applications.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] A well-designed edge platform would significantly outperform a traditional cloud-based system.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Some applications rely on short response times, making edge computing a significantly more feasible option than cloud computing.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Examples range from IoT to autonomous driving, anything health or human / public safety relevant, or involving human perception such as facial recognition, which typically takes a human between 370-620 ms to perform.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Edge computing is more likely to be able to mimic the same perception speed as humans, which is useful in applications such as augmented reality, where the headset should preferably recognize who a person is at the same time as the wearer does.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Due to the nearness of the analytical resources to the end users, sophisticated analytical tools and artificial intelligence tools can run on the edge of the system.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] This placement at the edge helps to increase operational efficiency and is responsible for many advantages to the system.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] In distributed AI systems on the edge, data compression is increasingly recognized as a foundational design layer to mitigate bandwidth constraints caused by the exchange of large models and high-resolution sensor streams.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] By using servers located on a local edge network to perform those computations, the video files only need to be transmitted in the local network.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Avoiding transmission over the internet results in significant bandwidth savings and therefore increases efficiency.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] If the recognition is performed locally, it is possible to send the recognized text to the cloud rather than audio recordings, significantly reducing the amount of required bandwidth.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Edge application services reduce the volumes of data that must be moved, the consequent traffic, and the distance that data must travel.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] That provides lower latency and reduces transmission costs.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Computation offloading for real-time applications, such as facial recognition algorithms, showed considerable improvements in response times, as demonstrated in early research.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Further research showed that using resource-rich machines called cloudlets or micro data centers near mobile users, which offer services typically found in the cloud, provided improvements in execution time when some of the tasks are offloaded to the edge node.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] On the other hand, offloading every task may result in a slowdown due to transfer times between device and nodes, so depending on the workload, an optimal configuration can be defined.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] An IoT-based power grid system enables communication of electricity and data to monitor and control the power grid, which makes energy management more efficient.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] Other notable applications include connected cars, self-driving cars, smart cities, Industry 4.0, home automation, missiles,, satellite systems , as well as frameworks such as MediaPipe.
[src:cloudflare-d1/edge-computing] The growing field of **edge artificial intelligence** (edge AI or edge intelligence, sometimes referred to as "local AI" or "on-device AI") implements artificial intelligence in an edge computing environment, on the device or close to where data is collected.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] A **relational database** (**RDB**) is a database based on the relational model of data, as proposed by E.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] A Relational Database Management System (RDBMS) is a type of database management system that stores data in a structured format using rows and columns.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Many relational database systems are equipped with the option of using SQL (Structured Query Language) for querying and updating the database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] The concept of relational database was defined by E.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Codd introduced the term *relational* in his research paper "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] In this paper and later papers, he defined what he meant by *relation*.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] One well-known definition of what constitutes a relational database system is composed of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Provide relational operators to manipulate the data in tabular form.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] In 1974, IBM began developing System R, a research project to develop a prototype RDBMS.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] The first system sold as an RDBMS was Multics Relational Data Store (June 1976).
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Oracle was released in 1979 by Relational Software, now Oracle Corporation.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Other examples of an RDBMS include IBM Db2, SAP Sybase ASE, and Informix.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] In 1984, the first RDBMS for Macintosh began being developed, code-named Silver Surfer, and was released in 1987 as 4th Dimension and known today as 4D.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] The most common definition of an RDBMS is a product that presents a view of data as a collection of rows and columns, even if it is not based strictly upon relational theory.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] By this definition, RDBMS products typically implement some but not all of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] A second school of thought argues that if a database does not implement all of Codd's rules (or the current understanding on the relational model, as expressed by Christopher J.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Date, Hugh Darwen and others), it is not relational.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] This view, shared by many theorists and other strict adherents to Codd's principles, would disqualify most DBMSs as not relational.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] For clarification, they often refer to some RDBMSs as *truly-relational database management systems* (TRDBMS), naming others *pseudo-relational database management systems* (PRDBMS).
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] As of 2009, most commercial relational DBMSs employ SQL as their query language.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Alternative query languages have been proposed and implemented, notably the pre-1996 implementation of Ingres QUEL.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] A relational model organizes data into one or more tables (or "relations") of columns and rows, with a unique key identifying each row.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Generally, each table/relation represents one "entity type" (such as customer or product).
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] The rows represent instances of that type of entity (such as "Lee" or "chair") and the columns represent values attributed to that instance (such as address or price).
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Each row in a table has its own unique key.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Rows in a table can be linked to rows in other tables by adding a column for the unique key of the linked row (such columns are known as foreign keys).
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Codd showed that data relationships of arbitrary complexity can be represented by a simple set of concepts.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Part of this processing involves consistently being able to select or modify one and only one row in a table.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Therefore, most physical implementations have a unique primary key (PK) for each row in a table.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] When a new row is written to the table, a new unique value for the primary key is generated; this is the key that the system uses primarily for accessing the table.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] System performance is optimized for PKs.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Other, more natural keys may also be identified and defined as alternate keys (AK).
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Often several columns are needed to form an AK (this is one reason why a single integer column is usually made the PK).
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Both PKs and AKs have the ability to uniquely identify a row within a table.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Additional technology may be applied to ensure a unique ID across the world, a globally unique identifier, when there are broader system requirements.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] The primary keys within a database are used to define the relationships among the tables.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] When a PK migrates to another table, it becomes a foreign key (FK) in the other table.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] When each cell can contain only one value and the PK migrates into a regular entity table, this design pattern can represent either a one-to-one or one-to-many relationship.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Most relational database designs resolve many-to-many relationships by creating an additional table that contains the PKs from both of the other entity tables – the relationship becomes an entity; the resolution table is then named appropriately and the two FKs are combined to form a PK.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] The migration of PKs to other tables is the second major reason why system-assigned integers are used normally as PKs; there is usually neither efficiency nor clarity in migrating a bunch of other types of columns.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Relationships are a logical connection between different tables (entities), established on the basis of interaction among these tables.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] These relationships can be modelled as an entity-relationship model.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] In order for a database management system (DBMS) to operate efficiently and accurately, it must use ACID transactions.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Part of the programming within an RDBMS is accomplished using stored procedures (SPs).
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Often procedures can be used to greatly reduce the amount of information transferred within and outside of a system.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] For increased security, the system design may grant access to only the stored procedures and not directly to the tables.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Fundamental stored procedures contain the logic needed to insert new and update existing data.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] More complex procedures may be written to implement additional rules and logic related to processing or selecting the data.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] The relational database was first defined in June 1970 by Edgar Codd, of IBM's San Jose Research Laboratory.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Codd's view of what qualifies as an RDBMS is summarized in Codd's 12 rules.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] A relational database has become the predominant type of database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Other models besides the *relational model* include the hierarchical database model and the network model.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] In a relational database, a *relation* is a set of tuples that have the same attributes.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] A tuple usually represents an object and information about that object.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Objects are typically physical objects or concepts.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] A relation is usually described as a table, which is organized into rows and columns.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] All the data referenced by an attribute are in the same domain and conform to the same constraints.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] The relational model specifies that the tuples of a relation have no specific order and that the tuples, in turn, impose no order on the attributes.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Applications access data by specifying queries, which use operations such as *select* to identify tuples, *project* to identify attributes, and *join* to combine relations.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Relations can be modified using the *insert*, *delete*, and *update* operators.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] New tuples can supply explicit values or be derived from a query.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Similarly, queries identify tuples for updating or deleting.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] If the tuple contains a candidate or primary key then obviously it is unique; however, a primary key need not be defined for a row or record to be a tuple.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] The definition of a tuple requires that it be unique, but does not require a primary key to be defined.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Because a tuple is unique, its attributes by definition constitute a superkey.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] All data are stored and accessed via relations.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Relations that store data are called "base relations", and in implementations are called "tables".
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Other relations do not store data, but are computed by applying relational operations to other relations.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] These relations are sometimes called "derived relations".
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] In implementations these are called "views" or "queries".
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Derived relations are convenient in that they act as a single relation, even though they may grab information from several relations.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Also, derived relations can be used as an abstraction layer.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] A domain describes the set of possible values for a given attribute, and can be considered a constraint on the value of the attribute.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Mathematically, attaching a domain to an attribute means that any value for the attribute must be an element of the specified set.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] The character string *"ABC"*, for instance, is not in the integer domain, but the integer value *123* is.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Another example of domain describes the possible values for the field "CoinFace" as ("Heads","Tails").
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] So, the field "CoinFace" will not accept input values like (0,1) or (H,T).
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Constraints are often used to make it possible to further restrict the domain of an attribute.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] For instance, a constraint can restrict a given integer attribute to values between 1 and 10.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Constraints provide one method of implementing business rules in the database and support subsequent data use within the application layer.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] SQL implements constraint functionality in the form of check constraints.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Constraints restrict the data that can be stored in relations.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] These are usually defined using expressions that result in a Boolean value, indicating whether or not the data satisfies the constraint.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Constraints can apply to single attributes, to a tuple (restricting combinations of attributes) or to an entire relation.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Since every attribute has an associated domain, there are constraints (**domain constraints**).
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] The two principal rules for the relational model are known as **entity integrity** and **referential integrity**.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Every relation/table has a primary key, this being a consequence of a relation being a set.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] A primary key uniquely specifies a tuple within a table.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] While natural attributes (attributes used to describe the data being entered) are sometimes good primary keys, surrogate keys are often used instead.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] A surrogate key is an artificial attribute assigned to an object which uniquely identifies it (for instance, in a table of information about students at a school they might all be assigned a student ID in order to differentiate them).
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] The surrogate key has no intrinsic (inherent) meaning, but rather is useful through its ability to uniquely identify a tuple.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Another common occurrence, especially in regard to N:M cardinality is the composite key.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] A composite key is a key made up of two or more attributes within a table that (together) uniquely identify a record.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Foreign key refers to a field in a relational table that matches the primary key column of another table.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Foreign keys need not have unique values in the referencing relation.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] A foreign key can be used to cross-reference tables, and it effectively uses the values of attributes in the referenced relation to restrict the domain of one or more attributes in the referencing relation.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] A stored procedure is executable code that is associated with, and generally stored in, the database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Stored procedures usually collect and customize common operations, like inserting a tuple into a relation, gathering statistical information about usage patterns, or encapsulating complex business logic and calculations.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Frequently they are used as an application programming interface (API) for security or simplicity.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Implementations of stored procedures on SQL RDBMS's often allow developers to take advantage of procedural extensions (often vendor-specific) to the standard declarative SQL syntax.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Stored procedures are not part of the relational database model, but all commercial implementations include them.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] An index is one way of providing quicker access to data.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Indices can be created on any combination of attributes on a relation.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Queries that filter using those attributes can find matching tuples directly using the index (similar to Hash table lookup), without having to check each tuple in turn.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] This is analogous to using the index of a book to go directly to the page on which the information you are looking for is found, so that you do not have to read the entire book to find what you are looking for.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Relational databases typically supply multiple indexing techniques, each of which is optimal for some combination of data distribution, relation size, and typical access pattern.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Indices are usually implemented via B+ trees, R-trees, and bitmaps.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Indices are usually not considered part of the database, as they are considered an implementation detail, though indices are usually maintained by the same group that maintains the other parts of the database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] The use of efficient indexes on both primary and foreign keys can dramatically improve query performance.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] This is because B-tree indexes result in query times proportional to log(n) where n is the number of rows in a table and hash indexes result in constant time queries (no size dependency as long as the relevant part of the index fits into memory).
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Queries made against the relational database, and the derived relvars in the database are expressed in a relational calculus or a relational algebra.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] In his original relational algebra, Codd introduced eight relational operators in two groups of four operators each.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Other operators have been introduced or proposed since Codd's introduction of the original eight including relational comparison operators and extensions that offer support for nesting and hierarchical data, among others.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Normalization was first proposed by Codd as an integral part of the relational model.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] It encompasses a set of procedures designed to eliminate non-simple domains (non-atomic values) and the redundancy (duplication) of data, which in turn prevents data manipulation anomalies and loss of data integrity.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] The most common forms of normalization applied to databases are called the normal forms.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database".
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] RDBMS is an extension of that initialism that is sometimes used when the underlying database is relational.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] An alternative definition for a **relational database management system** is a database management system (DBMS) based on the relational model.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Most databases in widespread use today are based on this model.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] RDBMSs have been a common option for the storage of information in databases used for financial records, manufacturing and logistical information, personnel data, and other applications since the 1980s.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Relational databases have often replaced legacy hierarchical databases and network databases, because RDBMS were easier to implement and administer.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] However, due to the expanse of technologies, such as horizontal scaling of computer clusters, NoSQL databases have recently become popular as an alternative to RDBMS databases.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM in the period 1988 to 1994.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] DRDA enables network connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:cloudflare-d1/relational-database] According to research company Gartner, in 2011, the five leading proprietary software relational database vendors by revenue were Oracle (48.8%), IBM (20.2%), Microsoft (17.0%), SAP including Sybase (4.6%), and Teradata (3.7%).
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:cloudflare-d1/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] Many programming languages have bindings to the SQLite library.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] It generally follows PostgreSQL syntax, but does not enforce type checking by default.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] This means that one can, for example, insert a string into a column defined as an integer.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] Although it is a lightweight embedded database, SQLite implements most of the SQL standard and the relational model, including transactions and ACID guarantees.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] However, it omits many features implemented by other databases, such as materialized views and complete support for triggers and ALTER TABLE statements.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] Richard Hipp designed SQLite in the spring of 2000 while working for General Dynamics on contract with the United States Navy.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] Hipp was designing software used for a damage-control system aboard guided-missile destroyers; the damage-control system originally used HP-UX with an Informix database back-end.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] In August 2000, version 1.0 of SQLite was released, with storage based on gdbm (GNU Database Manager).
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] In September 2001, SQLite 2.0 replaced gdbm with a custom B-tree implementation, adding transaction capability.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] In June 2004, SQLite 3.0 added internationalization, manifest typing, and other major improvements, partially funded by America Online.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] In 2011, Hipp announced his plans to add a NoSQL interface to SQLite, as well as announcing UnQL, a functional superset of SQL designed for document-oriented databases.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] SQLite is one of four formats recommended for long-term storage of datasets approved for use by the Library of Congress.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] SQLite was designed to allow the program to be operated without installing a database management system or requiring a database administrator.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] Unlike client–server database management systems, the SQLite engine has no standalone processes with which the application program communicates.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] Due to the serverless design, SQLite applications require less configuration than client–server databases.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] SQLite is called *zero-configuration* because configuration tasks such as service management, startup scripts, and password- or GRANT-based access control are unnecessary.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] Access control is handled through the file-system permissions of the database file.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] Databases in client–server systems use file-system permissions that give access to the database files only to the daemon process, which handles its locks internally, allowing concurrent writes from several processes.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] SQLite stores the entire database, consisting of definitions, tables, indices, and data, as a single cross-platform file, allowing several processes or threads to access the same database concurrently.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] It implements this simple design by locking the database file during writing.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] Write access may fail with an error code, or it can be retried until a configurable timeout expires.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] SQLite read operations can be multitasked, though due to the serverless design, writes can only be performed sequentially.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] This concurrent access restriction does not apply to temporary tables, and it is relaxed in version 3.7 as write-ahead logging (WAL) enables concurrent reads and writes.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] Since SQLite has to rely on file-system locks, it is not the preferred choice for write-intensive deployments.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] SQLite uses PostgreSQL as a reference platform.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] "What would PostgreSQL do" is used to make sense of the SQL standard.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] One major deviation is that, with the exception of primary keys, SQLite does not enforce type checking; the type of a value is dynamic and not strictly constrained by the schema (although the schema will trigger a conversion when storing, if such a conversion is potentially reversible).
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] SQLite implements most of the SQL-92 standard for SQL, but lacks some features.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] For example, it only partially provides triggers and cannot write to views (however, it provides INSTEAD OF triggers that provide this functionality).
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] Its support of ALTER TABLE statements is limited.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] SQLite uses an unusual type system for an SQL-compatible DBMS: instead of assigning a type to a column as in most SQL database systems, types are assigned to individual values; in language terms it is *dynamically typed*.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] Moreover, it is *weakly typed* in some of the same ways that Perl is: one can insert a string into an integer column (although SQLite will try to convert the string to an integer first, if the column's preferred type is integer).
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] This adds flexibility to columns, especially when bound to a dynamically typed scripting language.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] However, the technique is not portable to other SQL products.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] A common criticism is that SQLite's type system lacks the data integrity mechanism provided by statically typed columns, although it can be emulated with constraints like `CHECK(typeof(x)='integer')`.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] In 2021, support for static typing was added through STRICT tables, which enforce datatype constraints for columns.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] Tables normally include a hidden *rowid* index column, which provides faster access.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] If a table includes an INTEGER PRIMARY KEY column, SQLite will typically optimize it by treating it as an alias for the *rowid*, causing the contents to be stored as a strictly typed 64-bit signed integer and changing its behavior to be somewhat like an auto-incrementing column.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] SQLite includes an option to create a table without a rowid column, which can save disk space and improve lookup speed.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] WITHOUT ROWID tables are required to have a primary key.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] SQLite supports foreign key constraints, although they are disabled by default and must be manually enabled with a PRAGMA statement.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] Stored procedures are not supported; this is an explicit choice by the developers to favor simplicity, as the typical use case of SQLite is to be embedded inside a host application that can define its own procedures around the database.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] SQLite does not have full Unicode support by default for backwards compatibility and due to the size of the Unicode tables, which are larger than the SQLite library.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] Full support for Unicode case-conversions can be enabled through an optional extension.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] SQLite supports full-text search through its FTS5 loadable extension, which allows users to efficiently search for a keyword in a large number of documents similar to how search engines search webpages.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] SQLite includes support for working with JSON through its *json1* extension, which is enabled by default since 2021.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] SQLite's JSON functions can handle JSON5 syntax since 2023.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] In 2024, SQLite added support for JSONB, a binary serialization of SQLite's internal representation of JSON.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] Using JSONB allows applications to avoid having to parse the JSON text each time it is processed and saves a small amount of disk space.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] In May 2025, the 25th‑anniversary release SQLite 3.50.0 introduced additional features, including new Unicode functions (`unistr()` and `unistr_quote()`), a new API (`sqlite3_setlk_timeout()`) for setting lock timeouts, improved command‑line tools and rsync utility enhancements, and optimized JSONB.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] The maximum supported size for an SQLite database file is 281 terabytes.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] SQLite normally stores every table and index in a SQLite database in a single ordinary disk file.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] Alternatively, SQLite can be told to keep a SQL database entirely in memory as an in-memory database with the `:memory:` connection string.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] SQLite's code is hosted with Fossil, a distributed version control system that uses SQLite as a local cache for its non-relational database format, and SQLite's SQL as an implementation language.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] A standalone command-line shell program called *sqlite3* is provided in SQLite's distribution.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] It can be used to create a database, define tables, insert and change rows, run queries and manage an SQLite database file.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] It also serves as an example for writing applications that use the SQLite library.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] SQLite uses automated regression testing prior to each release.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] Over 2 million tests are run as part of a release's verification.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] The SQLite library has 156,000 lines of source code, while all the test suites combined add up to 92 million lines of test code.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] SQLite's tests simulate a number of exceptional scenarios, such as power loss and I/O errors, in addition to testing the library's functionality.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] Starting with the August 10, 2009 release of SQLite 3.6.17, SQLite releases have 100% branch test coverage, one of the components of code coverage.
[src:cloudflare-d1/sqlite] SQLite has four different test harnesses: the original public-domain TCL tests, the proprietary C-language TH3 test suite, the SQL Logic Tests, which check SQLite against other SQL databases, and the dbsqlfuzz proprietary fuzzing engine.
